    {
      "title": "Stress shift and phonetic transcription",
      "html": "<p><b>Stress shift</b> occurs when the same spelling is stressed on different syllables depending on whether the word is a noun/adjective or a verb.</p>\n  <table style=\"width:100%;border-collapse:collapse\"><tr><th style=\"text-align:left;padding:4px 8px\">Word</th><th style=\"padding:4px 8px\">Noun / adj.</th><th style=\"padding:4px 8px\">Verb</th></tr>\n  <tr><td>record</td><td>'RE-cord</td><td>re-'CORD</td></tr>\n  <tr><td>present</td><td>'PRE-sent</td><td>pre-'SENT</td></tr>\n  <tr><td>object</td><td>'OB-ject</td><td>ob-'JECT</td></tr>\n  <tr><td>contract</td><td>'CON-tract</td><td>con-'TRACT</td></tr>\n  <tr><td>increase</td><td>'IN-crease</td><td>in-'CREASE</td></tr>\n  <tr><td>subject</td><td>'SUB-ject</td><td>sub-'JECT</td></tr>\n  <tr><td>conflict</td><td>'CON-flict</td><td>con-'FLICT</td></tr></table>\n  <h4>Phonetic transcription</h4>\n  <p>Write words in IPA between slashes: <i>cat /kæt/, night /naɪt/, laughter /ˈlɑːftə/, education /ˌedʒʊˈkeɪʃn/</i>. Learn to identify vowels, consonants, and mark primary (ˈ) and secondary (ˌ) stress.</p>",
      "examples": [
        {
          "q": "Transcribe: <i>cat, night, book, learn</i>.",
          "a": "/kæt/, /naɪt/, /bʊk/, /lɜːn/."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Rhyme patterns and rhythmic structures",
      "html": "<p><b>Rhyme</b> is the repetition of the same or similar sounds at the ends of words. In poetry, rhyme schemes are labelled with letters (a, b, c…):</p>\n  <ul>\n    <li><b>Couplet</b>: aa bb.</li>\n    <li><b>Alternate</b>: abab.</li>\n    <li><b>Envelope</b>: abba.</li>\n  </ul>\n  <p><b>Rhythm</b> in speech comes from stressed and unstressed syllables. English is a <b>stress-timed</b> language: stressed syllables occur at roughly equal intervals, and unstressed ones are compressed between them.</p>\n  <p>In poetry, this becomes <b>metre</b>: a foot such as iambic (u ' u ') or trochaic (' u ' u) repeats a pattern.</p>",
      "examples": [
        {
          "q": "Give the rhyme scheme: <br/>'The road was long, / The night was dark, / He sang a song, / And left his mark.'",
          "a": "abab — alternate rhyme (long/song, dark/mark)."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Oral English examination practice",
      "html": "<p>Typical WAEC / NECO Oral English items:</p>\n  <ol>\n    <li><b>Vowel selection</b>: pick the word with the same vowel as a given word.</li>\n    <li><b>Consonant selection</b>: pick the word with the same consonant sound.</li>\n    <li><b>Rhyme</b>: pick the word that rhymes with a given word.</li>\n    <li><b>Stress</b>: pick where the stress falls (1st, 2nd, 3rd syllable) or the odd word out by stress pattern.</li>\n    <li><b>Emphatic stress</b>: given a sentence with a bold word, identify the correct implication.</li>\n    <li><b>Function of stress</b>: identify a noun/verb pair.</li>\n  </ol>\n  <h4>Practice tips</h4>\n  <ul><li>Learn the IPA symbols by heart.</li>\n  <li>Practise minimal pairs: <i>ship/sheep, cat/cut, bit/beat</i>.</li>\n  <li>Read aloud paying attention to stress and intonation.</li></ul>",
      "examples": [
        {
          "q": "In <i>She 'called him a liar</i>, the emphasis on 'called' implies:",
          "a": "That she did not merely think it or say something less — she went as far as to <i>call</i> him a liar."
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
